          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>üá∑üá∫ Russia officially moves to legalize and make ties with the Taliban</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Russia is considering lifting its ban on the Taliban, though <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-02-04-2025-br1-6-without-formally-recognizing" target="_blank">without formally recognizing</a> its government. The Supreme Court will likely approve the move on April 17. Russia designated the Taliban a terrorist group in 2003, but since then, Moscow has strengthened ties with it after the US withdrawal in 2021. President Vladimir Putin now sees the Taliban as an ally against the Islamic State of Khorasan (IS-K), which claimed a deadly attack in Moscow in March.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">No country officially recognizes the Taliban. However, regional powers like Kazakhstan have eased some restrictions. The Taliban enforces strict Islamic law. Still, it has increased diplomatic efforts. This includes prisoner exchanges with the US during President Donald Trump's term.</p>
        </mj-text>
